`doSomething()` is only ever *called* once - that is, explicitly by you to retrieve the error based `Mono`. The `Mono` that&#39;s returned is indeed subscribed to again on each retry, but the method that originally returned it isn&#39;t called again.

The preferable thing to do here would be to refactor your code so that any side effects happen on subscribing to the `Mono`, eg:

	private Mono&lt;String&gt; doSomething() {
		return Mono.&lt;String&gt;error(new Error()).doOnSubscribe(s -&gt; System.out.println(&quot;doSomething&quot;));
	}

However, if that&#39;s not possible, then you can cause `doSomething()` to be executed as-is on each retry by using it as a supplier and flattening the result. If you want to go down that route, then replace:

    myClass.doSomething()

...with:

    Mono.fromSupplier(myClass::doSomething).flatMap(p-&gt;p)

